WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.996 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.996 --> 00:00:03.984 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:03.984 --> 00:00:15.450 align:middle line:90%


00:00:15.450 --> 00:00:19.430 align:middle line:10%
>> When we started years
ago, after "What the Bleep"

00:00:19.430 --> 00:00:23.750 align:middle line:10%
and people started waking up
to the idea that subjective

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:27.620 align:middle line:10%
changes, or subjective mind,
produces objective results

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:31.580 align:middle line:10%
in the external world, the most
common question we got was,

00:00:31.580 --> 00:00:33.300 align:middle line:10%
how do you do this?

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:34.760 align:middle line:90%
How do you make those changes?

00:00:34.760 --> 00:00:37.730 align:middle line:90%


00:00:37.730 --> 00:00:39.520 align:middle line:84%
If something's going
on inside of us,

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:42.070 align:middle line:84%
and it's producing some
result outside of us,

00:00:42.070 --> 00:00:44.240 align:middle line:84%
what is that process that's
going on inside of us

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:46.170 align:middle line:90%
that we could begin to measure?

00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:48.750 align:middle line:84%
And if it happens
once, it's an incident.

00:00:48.750 --> 00:00:51.470 align:middle line:84%
If it happens twice,
it's a coincidence.

00:00:51.470 --> 00:00:54.200 align:middle line:84%
But if you start seeing it
happen three and four and five

00:00:54.200 --> 00:00:56.650 align:middle line:84%
and six and seven times, now
you're looking at a trend.

00:00:56.650 --> 00:00:58.390 align:middle line:90%
You're looking at a pattern.

00:00:58.390 --> 00:01:01.640 align:middle line:84%
And anything that's
repeatable is science.

00:01:01.640 --> 00:01:06.690 align:middle line:90%


00:01:06.690 --> 00:01:10.204 align:middle line:90%
>> Chloe, where's your ear?

00:01:10.204 --> 00:01:11.070 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:01:11.070 --> 00:01:12.290 align:middle line:90%
Where's your head?

00:01:12.290 --> 00:01:13.180 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:14.670 align:middle line:90%
Where's your mouth?

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:17.210 align:middle line:90%
Where's your nose?

00:01:17.210 --> 00:01:19.400 align:middle line:90%
That's your eye.

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:21.860 align:middle line:84%
Our daughter is
about to turn one.

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:24.980 align:middle line:84%
And she was
exclusively breastfed

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:26.940 align:middle line:84%
until she was about six
or seven months old.

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:30.214 align:middle line:84%
So we didn't know that she
had any sort of allergies

00:01:30.214 --> 00:01:31.130 align:middle line:90%
or anything like that.

00:01:31.130 --> 00:01:33.530 align:middle line:84%
But she had eczema
for all this time,

00:01:33.530 --> 00:01:35.180 align:middle line:90%
and we didn't really know why.

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:36.242 align:middle line:90%
Are you hungry?

00:01:36.242 --> 00:01:38.090 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:38.090 --> 00:01:39.070 align:middle line:90%
Come on.

00:01:39.070 --> 00:01:40.220 align:middle line:90%
Let's go.

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:42.290 align:middle line:84%
And about seven
months old, we decided

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:44.360 align:middle line:84%
to start introducing
some formula.

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:46.790 align:middle line:84%
And the first night that
we tried to give it to her,

00:01:46.790 --> 00:01:50.150 align:middle line:84%
she kept batting it away
and batting it away.

00:01:50.150 --> 00:01:53.540 align:middle line:84%
And just shortly thereafter,
she vomited, and then

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:56.000 align:middle line:84%
her face began to swell,
and her ears began to swell,

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.700 align:middle line:84%
and she was covered in
a rash from head to toe.

00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:00.590 align:middle line:84%
And we went to
the emergency room

00:02:00.590 --> 00:02:04.880 align:middle line:84%
and found out that she had a
really severe dairy allergy.

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:06.800 align:middle line:84%
The eczema that
she was presenting

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:09.800 align:middle line:84%
was actually from
foods that she was

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:12.020 align:middle line:84%
getting passed through my
milk all along the way,

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:13.640 align:middle line:84%
before she ever
even had the dairy.

00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:18.630 align:middle line:90%


00:02:18.630 --> 00:02:24.820 align:middle line:84%
>> In 2007, my husband, he
committed suicide in jumping

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:27.760 align:middle line:90%
off a building in Amsterdam.

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:33.850 align:middle line:84%
And after that, I was actually
a whole year stressed out,

00:02:33.850 --> 00:02:37.660 align:middle line:90%
in pain, emotionally upset.

00:02:37.660 --> 00:02:39.110 align:middle line:90%
I was angry.

00:02:39.110 --> 00:02:42.520 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know how to
continue my life without him

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:44.840 align:middle line:84%
and the kids not
having a father.

00:02:44.840 --> 00:02:47.860 align:middle line:90%


00:02:47.860 --> 00:02:51.480 align:middle line:84%
For three or four
months, I couldn't sleep.

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:53.610 align:middle line:84%
And then I started
using alcohol.

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:55.980 align:middle line:84%
I started drinking
two glasses of wine

00:02:55.980 --> 00:02:58.460 align:middle line:90%
so I could get into sleep.

00:02:58.460 --> 00:03:00.360 align:middle line:84%
But in the morning
when I would wake up,

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:04.710 align:middle line:84%
the whole emotional state in
which I was in at that time

00:03:04.710 --> 00:03:07.770 align:middle line:84%
was there, immediately
popped up again.

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:08.760 align:middle line:90%
I couldn't relax.

00:03:08.760 --> 00:03:10.500 align:middle line:90%
But I kept on going.

00:03:10.500 --> 00:03:15.600 align:middle line:84%
And then one year later, a
Friday, I was at my work.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:16.720 align:middle line:90%
I was tired.

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:18.390 align:middle line:90%
I was stressed out.

00:03:18.390 --> 00:03:21.990 align:middle line:84%
And then from one
moment and the other,

00:03:21.990 --> 00:03:25.530 align:middle line:84%
I was talking to two
colleagues, and then I

00:03:25.530 --> 00:03:27.480 align:middle line:90%
couldn't stand up anymore.

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:28.775 align:middle line:90%
I couldn't walk.

00:03:28.775 --> 00:03:32.170 align:middle line:90%
[SIREN]

00:03:32.170 --> 00:03:36.240 align:middle line:84%
And they called immediately
emergency number.

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:39.460 align:middle line:84%
And then I was taken
to the hospital.

00:03:39.460 --> 00:03:42.300 align:middle line:84%
And I was in the
hospital for a few weeks.

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:44.640 align:middle line:84%
They didn't know what
was really going on.

00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:48.600 align:middle line:84%
They called it an
autoimmune reaction.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:52.740 align:middle line:84%
And I was released after six
weeks out of the hospital

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:56.370 align:middle line:84%
without knowing the cause
of why I couldn't walk,

00:03:56.370 --> 00:04:01.500 align:middle line:84%
without any really good
treatment, because they

00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:02.745 align:middle line:90%
couldn't find the cause.

00:04:02.745 --> 00:04:07.530 align:middle line:90%


00:04:07.530 --> 00:04:10.230 align:middle line:84%
>> I was in two wars-- the
Persian Gulf War and the Iraq

00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:11.460 align:middle line:90%
War.

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:13.320 align:middle line:90%
I found out I had PTSD.

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:16.260 align:middle line:84%
And the VA's
response to that was

00:04:16.260 --> 00:04:19.170 align:middle line:84%
to use all these
different medications.

00:04:19.170 --> 00:04:21.329 align:middle line:84%
And having a doctor
of pharmacy degree,

00:04:21.329 --> 00:04:24.490 align:middle line:84%
I knew that that would
just more or less

00:04:24.490 --> 00:04:28.260 align:middle line:84%
put a Band-Aid on what I was
going, through that I really

00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:34.650 align:middle line:84%
needed to get to the core trauma
to deal with those experiences

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:35.750 align:middle line:90%
that I did experience.

00:04:35.750 --> 00:04:39.790 align:middle line:90%


00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:45.380 align:middle line:84%
And so I wanted to find
a non-pharmacological way

00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:52.130 align:middle line:84%
of dealing with the
emotions I was feeling.

00:04:52.130 --> 00:04:54.620 align:middle line:84%
>> So we took her off all of
the solids that she was eating

00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:58.310 align:middle line:84%
and slowly started to introduce
foods one by one to figure out

00:04:58.310 --> 00:05:00.770 align:middle line:90%
what she was allergic to.

00:05:00.770 --> 00:05:03.440 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it was pretty
much everything.

00:05:03.440 --> 00:05:05.790 align:middle line:84%
We felt really responsible
and felt really bad.

00:05:05.790 --> 00:05:09.260 align:middle line:84%
I did, because I'm shoving
these things into her body,

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:13.080 align:middle line:84%
not knowing that she's
sensitive to them.

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:15.830 align:middle line:84%
So just a lot of conflicting
emotions, a lot of guilt,

00:05:15.830 --> 00:05:18.060 align:middle line:90%
a lot of worry as a mom.

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:19.990 align:middle line:84%
It was a constant
process of saying,

00:05:19.990 --> 00:05:23.540 align:middle line:84%
OK, well, I'm just going to try
a little bite of strawberry.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:25.730 align:middle line:84%
And so there was all that
hope that would build up,

00:05:25.730 --> 00:05:27.110 align:middle line:84%
and then she would
have a reaction again.

00:05:27.110 --> 00:05:28.940 align:middle line:84%
And so then there was
the guilt afterwards,

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:30.942 align:middle line:84%
like what was I thinking
trying it again?

00:05:30.942 --> 00:05:32.900 align:middle line:84%
When we went to the
doctor, they talked so much

00:05:32.900 --> 00:05:34.790 align:middle line:90%
about her limitations.

00:05:34.790 --> 00:05:36.290 align:middle line:84%
And that's just
not a word that you

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:38.190 align:middle line:84%
want to hear when it
comes to your kiddo.

00:05:38.190 --> 00:05:42.990 align:middle line:90%


00:05:42.990 --> 00:05:45.620 align:middle line:84%
>> I lost everything
in that year.

00:05:45.620 --> 00:05:46.780 align:middle line:90%
I was disabled.

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:47.580 align:middle line:90%
I couldn't walk.

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:49.390 align:middle line:90%
I lost my husband.

00:05:49.390 --> 00:05:51.240 align:middle line:90%
I went really down.

00:05:51.240 --> 00:05:53.730 align:middle line:90%
I got ulcers in my mouth.

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:57.400 align:middle line:84%
I got the ulcers in
the certain epithelium

00:05:57.400 --> 00:06:02.070 align:middle line:84%
of the mucus membranes in
the mouth and esophagus.

00:06:02.070 --> 00:06:04.050 align:middle line:90%
I was in constant pain.

00:06:04.050 --> 00:06:06.330 align:middle line:84%
And that was actually
the reflection

00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:07.800 align:middle line:90%
of how I felt inside.

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:09.120 align:middle line:90%
I was in pain.

00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:13.960 align:middle line:84%
In January 2011, I got the
diagnosis of esophagus cancer.

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:15.270 align:middle line:90%
I had two options--

00:06:15.270 --> 00:06:17.670 align:middle line:90%
chemo or operation.

00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:21.330 align:middle line:84%
And the operation, I said,
I'm not going to take.

00:06:21.330 --> 00:06:23.590 align:middle line:90%
I just try first the chemo.

00:06:23.590 --> 00:06:26.250 align:middle line:90%
Maybe that will help.

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:28.890 align:middle line:84%
From the moment they
gave me the first chemo,

00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:32.130 align:middle line:84%
my heart rate went up
to 200 and something.

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:34.000 align:middle line:90%
I felt nauseous.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:35.280 align:middle line:90%
I felt so awful.

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:39.600 align:middle line:84%
Then I actually at that moment
already wanted to pull it out.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:43.560 align:middle line:84%
But they told me to keep
it going in because that

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:46.110 align:middle line:90%
would be the best thing to do.

00:06:46.110 --> 00:06:49.800 align:middle line:84%
But two hours later, I
said, I want this out.

00:06:49.800 --> 00:06:51.780 align:middle line:90%
I want this out of my body.

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:53.460 align:middle line:84%
So then they pulled
the infusion out,

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:55.180 align:middle line:84%
and I walked out
of the hospital.

00:06:55.180 --> 00:06:59.050 align:middle line:84%
And I said, I'm not going
to go back there anymore.

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:03.310 align:middle line:84%
>> If you keep the brain
sustained in the high level

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:06.790 align:middle line:84%
of emergency mode, and the
adrenal chemicals are running

00:07:06.790 --> 00:07:10.150 align:middle line:84%
in the body, the brain wave
patterns that are created are

00:07:10.150 --> 00:07:12.250 align:middle line:90%
no longer in rhythm.

00:07:12.250 --> 00:07:14.150 align:middle line:90%
They are no longer synchronized.

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:18.040 align:middle line:84%
They are dyssynchronized, or
disintegrated, or disorderly.

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:21.160 align:middle line:10%
And that type of disorderly
pattern in the brain

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:24.160 align:middle line:10%
sends a disorderly signal down
the central nervous system

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:29.190 align:middle line:10%
and causes disorderly messages
to the rest of the body.

00:07:29.190 --> 00:07:35.310 align:middle line:84%
>> I had one huge thought, since
2007, I was carrying around--

00:07:35.310 --> 00:07:38.110 align:middle line:84%
my husband should not
have committed suicide,

00:07:38.110 --> 00:07:41.220 align:middle line:84%
and he should not have
left his children alone.

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:46.770 align:middle line:84%
So these thoughts actually
created the stress

00:07:46.770 --> 00:07:49.170 align:middle line:84%
in my body, the
anger, the sadness.

00:07:49.170 --> 00:07:51.510 align:middle line:84%
Like, my god, how could
he have done this?

00:07:51.510 --> 00:07:56.670 align:middle line:10%
>> If you look at the depression
that we're seeing as a society,

00:07:56.670 --> 00:07:59.970 align:middle line:10%
as you're seeing pharmaceutical
companies and all

00:07:59.970 --> 00:08:05.340 align:middle line:10%
the anti-depressant medication,
there's a crying out there

00:08:05.340 --> 00:08:07.350 align:middle line:10%
in the world right now
that people are in pain.

00:08:07.350 --> 00:08:16.190 align:middle line:90%


00:08:16.190 --> 00:08:20.330 align:middle line:84%
>> I think that
transformation is teachable.

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:25.220 align:middle line:84%
And I think that a new
model has to be developed.

00:08:25.220 --> 00:08:28.010 align:middle line:10%
My intention in
this work is really

00:08:28.010 --> 00:08:34.669 align:middle line:10%
to make it so simple and
provided in a language that

00:08:34.669 --> 00:08:38.330 align:middle line:10%
